**Average O(1):** with a good hash function, keys are distributed uniformly across buckets. get() computes hash → finds bucket → checks 1–2 entries.

**Worst case causes:**
1. **Bad hashCode():** all objects return the same hash (e.g. `return 42`) → all keys land in one bucket → O(n) linear search.
2. **Hash flooding attacks:** adversary crafts keys with the same hash (e.g. in HTTP parameter parsing) → DoS via O(n) lookup. Defense: Java randomises String hashCode seed per JVM startup (Java 8+).

**Java 8+ improvement (treeification):**
When a bucket's chain exceeds `TREEIFY_THRESHOLD = 8` entries AND total capacity ≥ 64, the chain converts to a Red-Black Tree → O(log n) lookup even in the worst case.

```java
// ❌ Terrible hashCode — breaks HashMap
class BadKey {
    @Override public int hashCode() { return 42; } // all keys → same bucket
    @Override public boolean equals(Object o) { ... }
}

// ✅ Good hashCode — from Objects.hash()
class GoodKey {
    String id; int value;
    @Override public int hashCode() { return Objects.hash(id, value); }
}
```

**Internal structure:** binary heap in a flat array. For node at index i:
- Left child: `2i + 1`
- Right child: `2i + 2`  
- Parent: `(i - 1) / 2`

**add(element) — O(log n):**
1. Place element at end of array
2. Sift up (swap with parent while element < parent) — at most log n swaps

**poll() → removes minimum — O(log n):**
1. Swap root with last element
2. Remove last
3. Sift down (swap with smaller child while out of order) — at most log n swaps

**peek() — O(1):** return array[0] (the minimum element)

```java
PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(); // min by default
PriorityQueue<Integer> maxHeap = new PriorityQueue<>(Comparator.reverseOrder());

// k-largest elements pattern
public int[] kLargest(int[] nums, int k) {
    PriorityQueue<Integer> minHeap = new PriorityQueue<>();
    for (int n : nums) {
        minHeap.offer(n);
        if (minHeap.size() > k) minHeap.poll(); // evict smallest
    }
    return minHeap.stream().mapToInt(i->i).toArray(); // remaining k-largest
}
```

**Heapify (build from existing array): O(n)** — not O(n log n) as commonly assumed. `new PriorityQueue<>(Collection)` heapifies in O(n).

**BFS — Breadth-First Search:**
- Uses a **Queue**
- Explores all neighbours at depth k before depth k+1
- **Guarantees shortest path** (fewest edges) in unweighted graphs

```java
void bfs(Graph g, int start) {
    Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[g.V()];
    q.offer(start); visited[start] = true;
    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int node = q.poll();
        for (int neighbor : g.adj(node)) {
            if (!visited[neighbor]) {
                visited[neighbor] = true;
                q.offer(neighbor);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**DFS — Depth-First Search:**
- Uses **Stack** (or recursion)
- Goes as deep as possible, backtracks when stuck
- Does NOT guarantee shortest path

**Use BFS for:** shortest path (unweighted), level-order tree traversal, finding all nodes within distance k.

**Use DFS for:** cycle detection, topological sort, connected components, maze solving, backtracking (N-queens, permutations), detecting if a path exists.

**Memory:** BFS can use O(V) memory (full level in queue). DFS uses O(depth) memory — better for very deep, narrow graphs.

**Binary search — O(log n), requires sorted array:**
```java
// Template: find exact target
public int binarySearch(int[] nums, int target) {
    int left = 0, right = nums.length - 1; // inclusive bounds
    while (left <= right) {               // ← <= not <
        int mid = left + (right - left) / 2; // ← avoid overflow (not (l+r)/2)
        if (nums[mid] == target)  return mid;
        else if (nums[mid] < target) left = mid + 1;
        else                         right = mid - 1;
    }
    return -1; // not found
}
```

**Common off-by-one mistakes:**
```java
// ❌ Bug 1: right = nums.length (out-of-bounds on nums[right])
int right = nums.length; // should be length - 1

// ❌ Bug 2: while (left < right) — misses the last element
while (left < right) // should be left <= right for exact search

// ❌ Bug 3: mid = (left + right) / 2 — integer overflow when both are large
int mid = (left + right) / 2; // use left + (right - left) / 2

// ❌ Bug 4: left = mid instead of mid + 1 — infinite loop when left == mid
left = mid; // should be mid + 1
```

**Java built-in:** `Arrays.binarySearch(arr, target)` — returns index if found, `-(insertionPoint) - 1` if not found (negative = not present).

**DP applies when:** a problem has overlapping subproblems (same sub-calculation done repeatedly) and optimal substructure (optimal solution built from optimal sub-solutions).

**Fibonacci — naive recursion: O(2^n)**
```java
int fib(int n) { return n <= 1 ? n : fib(n-1) + fib(n-2); }
// fib(5) computes fib(3) twice, fib(2) three times...
```

**Top-down (memoization): O(n) time, O(n) space**
```java
Map<Integer, Long> memo = new HashMap<>();
long fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    if (memo.containsKey(n)) return memo.get(n); // cache hit
    long result = fib(n-1) + fib(n-2);
    memo.put(n, result);
    return result;
}
```

**Bottom-up (tabulation): O(n) time, O(1) space**
```java
long fib(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return n;
    long prev2 = 0, prev1 = 1;
    for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        long curr = prev1 + prev2;
        prev2 = prev1;
        prev1 = curr;
    }
    return prev1;
}
```

**When to use which:**
- Top-down: easier to reason about, only computes needed states
- Bottom-up: no recursion stack, better cache performance, often faster in practice

**Floyd's algorithm (O(n) time, O(1) space):**
```java
public boolean hasCycle(ListNode head) {
    ListNode slow = head, fast = head;
    while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
        slow = slow.next;
        fast = fast.next.next;
        if (slow == fast) return true; // they met inside the cycle
    }
    return false; // fast reached end — no cycle
}
```

**Why it works:** if there's a cycle of length L, fast gains 1 step per iteration on slow. They meet within L iterations after slow enters the cycle.

**Finding the cycle start (bonus):**
```java
// After slow == fast, reset slow to head
// Advance both one step at a time
// They meet at the cycle start
ListNode cycleStart(ListNode head) {
    ListNode slow = head, fast = head;
    while (fast != null && fast.next != null) {
        slow = slow.next;
        fast = fast.next.next;
        if (slow == fast) break;
    }
    if (fast == null || fast.next == null) return null; // no cycle
    slow = head;
    while (slow != fast) { slow = slow.next; fast = fast.next; }
    return slow; // cycle start
}
```

**Alternative (O(n) space):** store visited nodes in a HashSet. If a node is seen twice, there's a cycle at that node. Less elegant but obvious.
